Title: Declassified army photos from the ’70s and ’80s look like they’ve been pulled from a magazine
Summary: Despite the ugly realities of war, military-adjacent aesthetics have enjoyed a long affiliation with the fashion industry and pop culture at large; from the mainstream use of camoflage prints and epaulettes on the shoulders of jackets to the widespread adoption of colors such as army green and khaki. These styles have made cameos on stage of late too: at the DNC and Lollapalooza (with the Harris-Walz campaign and Chappell Roan’s “Midwest Princess” tour, respectively).

Title: Dreamlike image of tadpoles in a lake wins Wildlife Photographer of the Year 2024
Summary: A magical underwater image of western toad tadpoles has won the 2024 Wildlife Photographer of the Year competition.

Title: Nobel Prize in medicine goes to two American biologists for work on the discovery of microRNA
Summary: The 2024 Nobel Prize in physiology or medicine has been awarded to US scientists Victor Ambros and Gary Ruvkun for their work on the discovery of microRNA, a molecule that governs how cells in the body function.

Title: Democrats grow anxious as Election Day nears
Summary: In the two-and-a-half months since Joe Biden ended his reelection bid, Kamala Harris swiftly secured the Democratic presidential nomination, headlined the party’s most rapturous convention since 2008, brought in hundreds of millions of dollars in new campaign donations and surged past Biden’s poll numbers from earlier this year.

Title: Teens are feeling pressured and burned out. Here’s how to help
Summary: Create a game plan for your life, rack up impressive grades and other achievements, and make sure you look great, too.

Title: Dress Codes: How the pussy-bow blouse became a political staple for Kamala Harris and other powerful women
Summary: “You do not lose your feminine qualities just because you are a prime minister,” Margaret Thatcher told British TV doctor Miriam Stoppard in a 1985 interview. “I often wear bows, they are rather softening … (and) rather pretty.”

Title: Small town in Thailand holds mass cremation for 23 who died in a school trip bus fire
Summary: Mourners wept and monks prayed at a cremation ceremony Tuesday in a small town in central Thailand for 23 young students and teachers who died in last week’s bus fire on a school field trip.

Title: Voters think America’s economy stinks. There’s nothing that will change that before the election
Summary: The job market is booming. Inflation has come back down to Earth. Americans are spending like crazy.

Title: Biden held ‘direct,’ 30-minute call with Netanyahu, White House says
Summary: President Joe Biden held a “direct,” 30-minute phone call with his Israeli counterpart Benjamin Netanyahu on Wednesday, their first conversation in almost two months and a chance to confer over Israel’s planned response to an Iranian ballistic missile attack.

Title: Kamala Harris has raised $1 billion since launching presidential campaign
Summary: Vice President Kamala Harris’ political team has raised $1 billion since entering the presidential race in late July, two sources familiar with the figure told CNN – marking a massive fundraising milestone in her campaign against former President Donald Trump.

Title: Qantas apologizes after R-rated film plays on every screen during Sydney-Tokyo flight
Summary: Things got unexpectedly racy  onboard a recent Qantas flight when an R-rated film was played on all the aircraft’s screens.

Title: The Gap comeback that might actually be working
Summary: Zac Posen points, emphatically, to a wall of blue — or rather a section of the wall filled with various swatches of navy and indigo, each imprinted with Gap’s narrow serif font logo on top.

Title: Scientists grow mystery tree from 1,000-year-old seed
Summary: “Jurassic Park,” and its genetically modified dinosaur escapees, is pure science fiction — it’s never going to happen. But it doesn’t mean that scientists aren’t interested in bringing the past back to life in some form.

Title: What this high school senior wants adults to know about classroom phone bans
Summary: When my friends and I walked into homeroom on the first day of school this year, my teacher told all of us to put our phones in a black plastic box on an old desk by the classroom door.

Title: Comet likely last seen when Neanderthals walked Earth could soon dazzle in the night sky
Summary: A recently discovered comet, known as C/2023 A3 Tsuchinshan–ATLAS, will make its closest approach of Earth on Saturday. Sky-gazers won’t want to miss the event since it may be the last time the comet will be seen in the night sky for another 80,000 years.

Title: What a doctor wishes women knew about their breasts
Summary: It’s time to think about your breasts — not just this month because it’s Breast Cancer Awareness Month, but every month.

Title: Investors went wild for China during its big holiday. But Chinese shoppers showed little of that optimism
Summary: Global investors went wild during China’s just-concluded Golden Week holiday by snapping up “everything” related to the country. But that optimism didn’t extend to shoppers and travelers in the world’s second-largest economy itself.

Title: Pilot dies aboard Turkish Airlines flight, forcing emergency landing in New York
Summary: A Turkish Airlines jetliner headed from Seattle to Istanbul made an emergency landing in New York on Wednesday after the captain died on board, an airline official said.

Title: Hezbollah publicly endorses Lebanon ceasefire efforts for the first time as Israel ramps up offensive
Summary: Hezbollah supports efforts aimed at achieving a ceasefire in Lebanon, its top official said on Tuesday, marking the first time the group has publicly endorsed a truce and not conditioned it on stopping the war in Gaza.

Title: Recession fears are fading. Now it’s time for America’s companies to back that up
Summary: Hopes for avoiding a recession are growing on Wall Street. Now, investors are looking for the coming earnings season to support that optimism.

Title: The undeniable crisis that’s not driving American voters
Summary: Warm water in the Gulf of Mexico that was predicted by climate scientists to feed harsher hurricanes helped supercharge September’s Hurricane Helene. That was before October’s monster storm, Milton, struck – the destruction of which will become clear in the days to come.

Title: Helicopter pilot who crashed into a hotel had drunk a ‘significant amount of alcohol,’ report finds
Summary: A pilot who died when he crashed a helicopter into a hotel in Australia had “significant blood alcohol content” during the unauthorized flight, according to an official report into the incident.

Title: Look of the Week: Meghan, Duchess of Sussex’s striking red gown, worn at a charity gala on Saturday, isn’t entirely new
Summary: There’s not much that is relatable about Meghan, Duchess of Sussex: from her rise to British royal notoriety to her achingly aspirational lifestyle brand, American Riviera Orchard. But on Saturday, a rare opportunity for connection presented itself when Meghan arrived at the Children’s Hospital Los Angeles 2024 Gala in a red Carolina Herrera dress she had previously worn in 2021.

Title: ‘Hotel in nature’: Inside the world’s best new skyscraper
Summary: Tropical plants creep up vast structural columns and dangle from ledges, hundreds of feet above the ground. Guests lounge around a lagoon-like swimming pool nestled away from the scorching midday sun. A series of soaring terraces sit within the tower’s frame, like caverns carved into a mountainside.

Title: Jürgen Klopp to become Red Bull’s global head of soccer in first job since leaving Liverpool
Summary: Jürgen Klopp was announced as the global head of soccer for the Red Bull group on Wednesday in what will be his first job since leaving Premier League giant Liverpool earlier this year.

Title: Republicans are challenging all aspects of mail-in voting in battleground states
Summary: After mail-in and absentee voting reached new levels in the 2020 election during the Covid-19 pandemic, a wave of lawsuits over the popular vote-casting methods this year is laying the groundwork for potential challenges to the outcome of the November presidential election.

Title: Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese apologizes for ‘hurtful’ Tourette’s syndrome jibe
Summary: Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has apologized after using an ableist slur to taunt political opponents in parliament.

Title: Lasers could take broadband where fiber optics can’t
Summary: In the internet industry, it’s known as the “last-mile” problem: Millions of people and businesses around the world aren’t able to access broadband because they’re missing the final leg of a broadband network, which connects the user to the backbone of the internet.

Title: For some riding out Milton along Florida’s west coast, ‘the alternatives weren’t too inviting’
Summary: With the rain already slicing diagonals into the water off this transformed mangrove island in St. Petersburg, Vivienne Marran stood firm in her choice.

Title: Biden and Harris step up public engagement about the dangers of Hurricane Milton
Summary: As Hurricane Milton barrels toward Florida, President Joe Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris have forcefully warned Americans multiple times on Wednesday about what the president is calling “the storm of the century.”

Title: Auction house withdraws shrunken heads and other human remains from sale following outcry
Summary: An auction house in England has withdrawn human remains, including shrunken heads and ancestral skulls, from sale following an outcry.

Title: Ariana Grande tells dejected ‘SNL’ cast that she doesn’t want to do ‘Wicked’ skits in hilarious promo
Summary: Ariana Grande would like to get a few things straight before she returns to host “Saturday Night Live” this weekend.

Title: Elon Musk’s X cleared to resume service in Brazil after it obeys court orders
Summary: Brazil’s Supreme Court cleared X to resume service in the country Tuesday, after the social media platform reversed course and started complying with court rulings that billionaire owner Elon Musk had previously vowed to resist.

Title: Inside the White House’s desperate scramble to swat down hurricane misinformation
Summary: In the aftermath of Hurricane Helene, senior Biden administration officials raced to engage in a round-the-clock effort to respond to what appeared to be an unprecedented amount of misinformation circling about the storm and the federal response to it.

Title: What the 1960 election can teach us about the peaceful transfer of power
Summary: The 1960 presidential election changed everything. It was the first to feature televised debates between the two major-party candidates. It was the first in which both candidates were born in the 20th century. And as is true in the current presidential campaign, the 1960 candidates were both fascinating characters.

Title: Rafael Nadal announces his upcoming retirement from tennis
Summary: Tennis legend Rafael Nadal has announced his upcoming retirement from the sport after a glittering career in which he amassed 22 grand slam titles.

Title: Are ‘manfluencers’ raising our sons?
Summary: My 17-year-old son had his headphones off, unlike a teenager, and was watching a YouTube video, very much like a teenager. That’s when I heard the words Andrew Tate, and my ears perked up.

Title: Scientists who used AI to ‘crack the code’ of almost all proteins win Nobel Prize in chemistry
Summary: The 2024 Nobel Prize in chemistry has been awarded to a trio of scientists who used artificial intelligence to “crack the code” of almost all known proteins, the “chemical tools of life.”

Title: Who is Hashem Safieddine, rumored to be the next Hezbollah chief?
Summary: The fate of a possible successor to Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah is unclear following an Israeli airstrike on Beirut.

Title: A$AP Rocky, Pharrell, Lewis Hamilton and Colman Domingo will co-chair a historic Met Gala
Summary: Though often underappreciated, menswear has been undergoing a renaissance on red carpets and runways. Next year, a landmark exhibition on Black suiting and sartorial codes will serve as the inspiration for fashion’s biggest night out.

Title: European spacecraft launches for ‘crash scene investigation’ of first planetary defense test
Summary: A European spacecraft and two shoebox-size satellites have launched to survey the aftermath from NASA’s DART mission, which intentionally slammed into an asteroid named Dimorphos and altered its orbit two years ago.

Title: Talks between Boeing and the machinists union break down as strike nears the one-month mark
Summary: Boeing and the union that represents 33,000 striking employees at the company say talks between the two have broken down and no new talks are scheduled.

Title: Jessica Campbell makes history and becomes first ever female assistant coach in the NHL
Summary: Jessica Campbell made history on the opening night of the National Hockey League (NHL) season by becoming the first ever female assistant coach in the league.

Title: This is the world’s smallest Rubik’s Cube. And it actually works
Summary: Japanese toymaker MegaHouse has unveiled a miniature Rubik’s Cube — one so tiny that you might need a pair of tweezers to solve it.

Title: Disney prices just went up again. Here’s how to get a discount
Summary: Disneyland fans woke up Wednesday morning to find about a 6% price increase on most park tickets and a price increase between 6% to 20% on annual passes, known as Magic Keys, for Disney’s original resort in California.

Title: Nearly 2,000 Florida gas stations have run out of fuel. Hurricane Milton could cause even more trouble
Summary: Gas stations in many areas of Florida are running out of gasoline, as residents prepare for Hurricane Milton.

Title: Your showerhead and toothbrush are teeming with viruses. But don’t panic – these microbes could save lives
Summary: The warm, damp environments of your showerhead and toothbrush are the perfect breeding ground for microbes, and a new study has identified hundreds of viruses that live there, showing the vast biodiversity to be found in the average home.

Title: Covid-19 may increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and deaths for three years after an infection, study suggests
Summary: Covid-19 could be a powerful risk factor for heart attacks and strokes for as long as three years after an infection, a large new study suggests.

Title: How horses can soothe the soul and help your mental health
Summary: Every October, World Mental Health Day tries to expand the conversation around mental health and brings awareness to the many ways you can improve your emotional well-being. When it comes to mental health, the solution is multi-faceted.

Title: Ratan Tata, Indian tycoon who took his empire global, dead at 86
Summary: Ratan Tata, the former chairman of Indian conglomerate Tata Group, has died at the age of 86, according to a statement from the firm.

Title: Devastation from Hurricane Helene could bring semiconductor chipmaking to a halt
Summary: The devastation in North Carolina in the wake of Hurricane Helene could have serious implications for a niche — but extremely important — corner of the tech industry.

Title: A severe geomagnetic storm could cause colorful auroras over Northern California and Alabama
Summary: Colorful auroras could be visible in areas of the United States such as Alabama and Northern California — much farther south than they typically appear — on Thursday evening due to a powerful solar flare and coronal mass ejection released from the sun, according to the National Weather Service’s Space Weather Prediction Center.

Title: When a massive asteroid wiped out the dinosaurs, ants began farming fungi
Summary: You have probably seen leaf-cutter ants carrying bits of plants, maybe in a nature documentary, at a science museum or in the “Circle of Life” song at the beginning of the 1994 Disney animated film “The Lion King.”

Title: Sean ‘Diddy’ Combs spending his time in jail preparing for his case and visiting with family, source says
Summary: Sean “Diddy” Combs has spent his three weeks in jail speaking with his defense attorneys, preparing for his case and receiving visiting from his family, a source close to the music producer told CNN.

Title: Large French ski resort to close as snow shortage leaves it struggling to build a future
Summary: A large French alpine ski resort faced with declining snowfalls is to close after it failed to find funds to turn its pistes into year-round attractions.

Title: Denver Nuggets head coach Michael Malone says he isn’t taking Nikola Jokić’s ‘greatness’ for granted heading into new season
Summary: The chance to win an NBA title doesn’t come around very often.

Title: ‘Zionists don’t deserve to live,’ suspended Columbia activist said. Now his group rescinds its apology and calls for violence
Summary: Nearly six months after Columbia University banned Khymani James, a Pro-Palestinian student activist, who said “Zionists don’t deserve to live,” the coalition that had apologized on his behalf rescinded its statement of regret – and advocated for armed resistance against Israel.

Title: ‘Our dreams were falling down the mountain’: American and British climbers stranded in the Himalayas for three days
Summary: Fay Manners and Michelle Dvorak were perched high on the snowy face of a Himalayan mountain when disaster struck their quest to become the first to summit its peak.

Title: ‘Godfather of AI’ shares Nobel Prize in physics for work on machine learning
Summary: The 2024 Nobel Prize in physics has been awarded to John Hopfield and Geoffrey Hinton for their fundamental discoveries in machine learning, which paved the way for how artificial intelligence is used today.

Title: CDC will start screening travelers from Rwanda to the US for Marburg virus
Summary: Amid an outbreak of Marburg virus in Rwanda, travelers coming into the United States who have been in Rwanda in the previous 21 days will be screened starting next week, the US Department of Health and Human Services announced Monday.

Title: Common heart conditions raise the risk of dementia, experts say
Summary: Keeping your brain sharp as you age has a lot to do with your heart — and the younger you start taking better care of it, the better — according to a new scientific statement published Thursday by the American Heart Association.

Title: The Nobel committee just entered the AI chat
Summary: This week, the Nobel prizes for physics and chemistry both featured work on the development and application of artificial intelligence. (Trendy choice? Absolutely. Serious choice? Also yes.)

Title: Senate candidate Dave McCormick led hedge fund that bet against some of Pennsylvania’s most iconic companies
Summary: In the years that Pennsylvania Senate candidate Dave McCormick led one of the world’s largest hedge funds, the firm bet millions of dollars  against some of the state’s biggest and most iconic companies, financial filings show.

Title: A couple walked from opposite ends of China’s Great Wall and met in the middle. Then they broke up
Summary: The Great Wall of China has inspired countless works of art in its more than 2,000-year history. Among the most famous is “The Great Wall Walk,” a dramatic 90-day performance that saw lovers Marina Abramović and Frank Uwe Laysiepen (the late German artist known as Ulay) trek towards each other from opposite ends of the landmark.

Title: Elon Musk is promising to unveil the future of Tesla tonight
Summary: Elon Musk and Tesla have pledged a game-changing moment in the company’s history Thursday night. It remains to be seen if they will actually deliver.

Title: Minnesota Lynx defeat Connecticut Sun to book record seventh WNBA Finals appearance
Summary: The Minnesota Lynx prevailed in a winner-takes-all Game 5 of the WNBA semifinals against the Connecticut Sun on Tuesday. With the 88-77 victory, the Lynx set a date with the New York Liberty in the WNBA Finals.
